For this contrived example you could use getters / setters instead of static properties to leverage interfaces:

```
type GenericStruct interface {
   GetName() string
}
```

And now any struct with a receiver called `GetName` will satisfy the `GenericStruct` interface:

```
type MyStruct struct {
  Name string
}

func (ms *MyStruct) GetName() string {
  return ms.Name
}
```

This could get messy with more complex structs, in which case you may want to consider the composition suggestion (typically achieved via [embedding](https://golang.org/doc/effective_go.html#embedding)) or a third party library such as [genny](https://github.com/cheekybits/genny)

