PushStreamContent will allow you to send a stream of bytes without buffering.

    var httpClient = new HttpClient();

    var request = new HttpRequestMessage() {
       RequestUri = ... ,
       Method = HttpMethod.POST,
       Content = new PushStreamContent(async (stream, httpContent, transportContext) =&gt;
           { 
              // write to the stream from where ever you are getting the bytes from
              stream.Close();
           })
    };
    
    await httpClient.SendAsync(request);

You can see from here https://github.com/aspnet/AspNetWebStack/blob/master/src/System.Net.Http.Formatting/PushStreamContent.cs#L113 that all PushStreamContent does is it receives the network stream from the HttpClientHandler via the SerializeToStream method and allows you to write directly to it.
    
I have a vague recollection of there being an issue with early versions of .NET 4 that actually prevented using chunked transport encoding.  I recall it being fixed but I&#39;m not 100% certain of it.  If chunked encoding is not working it is a problem in the HttpClientHandler end of the pipeline, not in HttpClient or PushStreamContent.

